620","1587":"1587","1673":"1673","1585":"1585","8 October 1637":"8. oktober 1637","1608":"1608","1607":"1607","1605":"1605","1637":"1637","Laverham,Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","St. John the Evangelist Churchyard, Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England"},"nl":{"1579–8 October 1637":"1579–8 oktober 1637","1579–1637":"1579–1637","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1605–1673":"1605–1673","1607–1637":"1607–1637","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1681":"1681","about 1608":"circa 1608","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1673":"1673","1585":"1585","8 October 1637":"8 oktober 1637","1608":"1608","1607":"1607","1605":"1605","1637":"1637","Laverham,Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","St. John the Evangelist Churchyard, Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1579–8 October 1637":"1579–8 October 1637","1579–1637":"1579–1637","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1605–1673":"1605–1673","1607–1637":"1607–1637","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1681":"1681","about 1608":"about 1608","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1673":"1673","1585":"1585","8 October 1637":"8 October 1637","1608":"1608","1607":"1607","1605":"1605","1637":"1637","Laverham,Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","St. John the Evangelist Churchyard, Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hammond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Almund</i>, in which Old English <i>Æthelmund</i> ‘noble protector’ and <i>Ealhmund</i> ‘temple protector’ have coalesced.","variant of   Allman   and   Allmand   both meaning ‘German’, assimilated by folk etymology to the vocabulary word denoting the tree."]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Breton, French, and English (Channel Islands): from the Breton, Old French, Middle English personal name <i>Hamon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. See also   Hammond  ."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): patronymic from the Norman personal name <i>Hamo</i>, <i>Hamon</i> (see   Hammond  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAmhsaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Amhsach</i>’ a byname meaning ‘mercenary soldier’ or ‘messenger’, from the adjective <i>amhasach</i> ‘aggressive’."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":6,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":8,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":21,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":41,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Hammond was born in 1579, in Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England as the son of William Hammond Sr. He married Banadicus Gooch in 1605, in Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 8 October 1637, in his hometown, at the age of 58, and was buried in Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"1579–8 October 1637":"1579–8. oktoober 1637","1579–1637":"1579–1637","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1605–1673":"1605–1673","1607–1637":"1607–1637","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1681":"1681","about 1608":"umbes 1608","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1673":"1673","1585":"1585","8 October 1637":"8. oktoober 1637","1608":"1608","1607":"1607","1605":"1605","1637":"1637","Laverham,Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","St. John the Evangelist Churchyard, Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1579–8 October 1637":"1579–8. lokakuuta 1637","1579–1637":"1579–1637","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1605–1673":"1605–1673","1607–1637":"1607–1637","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1681":"1681","about 1608":"noin 1608","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1673":"1673","1585":"1585","8 October 1637":"8. lokakuuta 1637","1608":"1608","1607":"1607","1605":"1605","1637":"1637","Laverham,Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England","St. John the Evangelist Churchyard, Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Slimbridge, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"1579–8 October 1637":"1579–8 octobre 1637","1579–1637":"1579–1637","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1605–1673":"1605–1673","1607–1637":"1607–1637","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1681":"1681","about 1608